pr_review_comment_body:
@Abdulrahman44 
Try removing RLI from the string
[code.docx](https://github.com/amueller/word_cloud/files/1973642/code.docx)

This looks like a breaking change as we are renaming the waiter from `DBSnapshotCompleted` to `DBSnapshotAvaliable`. However, I am not sure how useful it was given its configuration was this:
```
    "DBSnapshotCompleted": {
      "delay": 15,
      "operation": "DescribeDBSnapshots",
      "maxAttempts": 40,
      "acceptors": [
        {
          "expected": "DBSnapshotNotFound",
          "matcher": "error",
          "state": "success"
        },
        {
          "expected": "available",
          "matcher": "pathAll",
          "state": "success",
          "argument": "DBSnapshots[].Status"
        }
      ]
}
```
Looks like the first acceptor should have been a failure?

If the only difference between x >y and x<y is the sign, maybe we can avoid the code duplicate here.

```
if ( x = y) {

} else {
   // calculate data3
   if (x < y) {
       data3 *= -1
    }
}
```

For `Get()`, User only need specify a list of types, different from `Set()` which need values  either with `otOperationalDataset` which has the `(flag, value)`s or with `aTlvs` which has complete `(type, len, value)`s;  
And for `Get()`, passing `otOperationalDataset` has has the flag named as `mIsXXXSet` may bring some confusion, though noted in the doxygen; enumerating types in public header files instead might be enough to let User know the notion of types.

Thoughts?

I think the bit ordering could be fixed with a very minor modification to the code that was removed above.

```
bool IsChannelSet(uint8_t aChannel) const {		
    const uint8_t *mask = reinterpret_cast<const uint8_t *>(this) + sizeof(*this);		
    return (aChannel < (mMaskLength * 8)) ? ((mask[aChannel / 8] & (0x80 >> (aChannel % 8))) != 0) : false;		
}
````
